<TITLE> UK's Nationwide ups minimum deposit for home loans </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's second biggest mortgage lender, Nationwide, increased the deposit it requires from new borrowers to at least 10 percent on all but two of its products on Monday. Building society Nationwide, which provides about one in 10 UK mortgages, continued the trend of lenders restricting terms on their products and requiring bigger deposits in the face of a slowing housing market and economy. Nationwide said it will only lend new fixed-rate and tracker mortgages for 90 percent of the property, but will continue to offer 95 percent loans for first-time borrowers choosing a three-year fixed-rate or tracker deal. It also cut the maximum loan size to 500,000 pounds for new customers. The building society said new mortgages on its base mortgage rate will only be available directly -- cutting out brokers -- and a 25 percent deposit is needed. The changes will allow the lender "to maintain control of the volume of business the society is attracting ... in a controlled and prudent way", it said. The changes take effect from May 
